There are well-known personalities who are the face of their businesses.
People like Tony Robbins and Dave Ramsey.
If you are new to entrepreneurship you might emulate your mentors and heroes. However, please stop and
ask yourself, “Should I be the face of my company?”
There is no right or wrong answer here. It depends on your long-term goals.
Keep in mind how quickly customer tastes and technology can change. If you know without a doubt you’ll
be happy running your business 10 years from now, then great be the brand .
What happens if in a few years you want to add other writers to your blog, outsource it, or sell the business?
If you’ve baked your personality and image into the business as the brand few companies will want to buy it.
Later when you want to step away or allow others to takeover, there is a possibility the company will either
fall apart, tarnish your reputation, or both.
Even if the company remains successful. What if you simply no longer wish to be associated with the
company?
It would be very difficult, if not impossible, to untangle your image from the company.
Could their be a Dave Ramsey website, podcast, or radio show without Dave Ramsey? Doesn’t seem
possible to me.
So again it depends on your overall goal. If you are running a personal fitness business and cannot imagine
doing anything else. Go ahead and brand yourself.
If your running an online business selling products. You might want to consider using a logo and motto like
Sony. They might have people endorsing their brand. But the brand is a logo, not a person. Sony could be
bought and sold by many different holding companies and the brand image would remain the same.
Most entrepreneurs don’t consider their exit strategy. Nothing lasts forever. Once your personal story has
run its course how do you plan on keeping people engaged in the company? If you want your company to
stand the test of time it has to appeal to customers beyond following the trials and triumphs of a single
person.
What happens when you retire, sell the company, or die? Without an exit strategy there is no process to
handle these kinds of inevitable outcomes.
Here are two articles that explain branding from different points of view.
The Basics of Branding
Personal Branding 101
If you are running a small business or considering becoming an entrepreneur of any kind. I encourage you
to think about and research what kind of brand you want to build. It is essential to bake-in your exit strategy
from the start. That way if you create a killer app and get and offer from Google to buy your company, you’ll
have a strategy in place to handle it.
In summary, think about your long-term goals and your exit strategy.
This will help you create a brand that will work best for you.
